of the hill. From a distance it appeared to be no more than a jagged pillar of darkness, but on closer inspection one noted the door, and windows etched into its stone walls. The stone shone like liquid black, catching the silvery light of the moon on occasion, sending it back to the observers eyes in small shimmering waves. <br>
She sighed softly, it had been so long since she had returned to this place. Here was her haven. Not many man nor beast could breach its walls without her permission. A slim, pale hand ran over the smooth, silken textured stone as she contemplated what she was about to do. <br>
Drawing in a deep breath, she released it slowly as she uttered the enchantment that would unseal the door to her, and slowly, moving as though age where the weight upon her she entered the tower, perhaps for the last time. <br>
The door slid silently to close behind her, hiding her from any prying eyes that may have watched her entrance. <br>
Inside on the main floor, a circular rug helped keep the feet from a long exposure to the cold stone. The circular walls bedecked by row upon row of bookshelves crammed full with every map, book and partchment she had ever came across. Organized in a way that made sense only to her. Some shelves held various items used in her experiments. Others held jars and vials of potions, elixers and various sundry. <br>
The shelves where broken only by the fireplace that called to one to come and rest. Placed before it a soft, overstuffed chair begged the weary body to seat itself, beside it a small table held a tray, which sported a single glass and a bottle of dark amber liquid. <br>
To her right a spiral staircase would lead her to the next room above. There where three in all. The second held her study, where she conducted her experiments, incantations and evocations. The last was her room, that was by far the most spartan of the three. Only a single bed, dresser and closet graced it. <br>
Still moving slowly she slid from the tight Kael boots, boots of the invoker they called them, and settled into her chair. Deftly without a glance, she poured a single shot of brandy and sipped at it absently as her gaze rested upon the cold hearth. More a thought than an utterance had a fire suddenly spring to life and wearily Grey's silver eyes watched the dance of flames as she contemplated what her next move would be. To hole up here till death finally found her, was certainly the easiest way out. <br>
Her mind fluttered to past glories, adventures and even the misadventures. The failures, the losses and even the gains. For every step forward two back had been taken. It had'nt been an easy life filled with companionship and mirth. But one of mostly solitary wanderings. <br>
Most folks tended to shun, and even fear a wizard in their raiding parties. Unless serious damage was needed. So a wizard learned quickly how to fend for themselves. She recalled a conversation she had just the other night.. <br>
&quot;Whom do you serve?&quot; He had asked her, it was a good valid question and yet one so hard to answer.. who did she indeed serve? Her god Karana had long abandoned her ages past when she lay near death, her soul taken. Innoruuk had battled hard to keep her alive, but for what means she had never found the answer. Tunare had never done anything but bring her rage and grief. And this goddess of love.. pshaw! Love was an illusion that mortals used to chain one to their side till that ones usefullness had ended. So who in fact did she serve? <br>
Chaos, and Ballance.. those where the gods she served. For now, the Drow could be considered the &quot;Underdogs&quot; in this battle, for their numbers where few, though thier power made up for some of the lack. The &quot;Lightborn&quot; races far outnumbered them in sheer populace alone. And so, for now, till the balance was met, she would work to even the odds some for them. To give them a more equal ground to stand upon. <br>
She lunged suddenly to her feet with a feral growl of rage, her glass still half full shattered loudly againts the back of the hearth, the brandy feeding the flame to a roar. She fell back into her chair, so confused now as to where that had come from. These sudden urges.. and outbursts of rage, anger, pain. What where their origins, she could not say, perhaps one day she would learn the answer. Her hand moved to cover the pulsing ruby that dangled from a slender chain about her neck. Its glow simulating the beat of a heart, a soul entrapped in smooth, beautiful, cold stone....<br>
Madness, sheer chaotic, beautiful insanity.. <br>
