The clay glinted dully in the light. Tiny specks of gold, red, and blue could be seen refracting the light back at the sculpter. <br>
Sitting back she sighed softly in satisfaction as the lump of clay now perfectly resembled that of a god. Innoruuk. The likeness of it unmistakable. <br>
Muttering softly to herself she rose and retrieved the liquid needed to complete the process. Pouring it slowly over the idol she watched as the the thirsty clay soaked up the essences of the liquid. <br>
The gently lifting the likeness she moved to the kiln to fire it. Turning away from the heat of the kiln while the idol baked she moved to cleans the grime from her fingers. <br>
Not a single step was taken as the ever haunting pain returned. This time so severe as to drive her to her knees, a keening cry of suprise wrung from her as her clay encrusted fingers clenched into the ebon curls at her temples. <br>
Then darkness fell, as Grey collapsed to the cold stone floor unconcious. <br>
The voice, her only companion in the abyss of shadows she found herself in. Despair at once more returning to this place of half life welled inside of her. <br>
&quot;You cannot escape me.. even here.. &quot;<br>
The voice, as insidious as ever, filled the void. Echoing all around her. She curled into a fetal position, unconciously attempting to protect herself perhaps.<br>
&quot;Leave me be.. just go.. or finish it.. but do something.. end this.. &quot; she hissed softly as she came too. Her eyes blinking slowly open and realizing that she was once more safely enscounced in her tower. <br>
Safety.. but for how long? <br>
Madness, sheer utter, beautiful madness. <br>
With a worldweary sigh she rose and moved to take the idol from the kiln. It had over cooked, and splintered. Ruined.<br>
Growling softly in anger she tossed the broken idol to the bin, and returned to the potters wheel once more to begin again.  <p><center>Greystorm Ironheart</center>
